\v 20 \w Whatever|strong="H3605"\w* subject \w the|strong="H3605"\w* \w king|strong="H4428"\w* \w asked|strong="H1697"\w* \w them|strong="H1992"\w* \w about|strong="H5921"\w*, \w everything|strong="H3605"\w* \w that|strong="H3605"\w* \w required|strong="H1245"\w* \w wisdom|strong="H2451"\w* \w of|strong="H4428"\w* understanding,\f + \fr 1:20 \ft The Hebrew does not say “wisdom and understanding” as most versions translate it. Some argue that “wisdom of understanding” indicates a superlative, in that the highest form of wisdom is indicated. Others suggest that “understanding” qualifies the term “wisdom,” indicating that this wisdom did not include so-called Babylonian “wisdom” of astrology and divination etc.\f* \w he|strong="H3605"\w* \w found|strong="H4672"\w* \w them|strong="H1992"\w* \w ten|strong="H6235"\w* \w times|strong="H3027"\w* \w better|strong="H3027"\w* \w than|strong="H5921"\w* \w all|strong="H3605"\w* \w the|strong="H3605"\w* \w magicians|strong="H2748"\w* \w and|strong="H4428"\w* enchanters \w in|strong="H5921"\w* \w his|strong="H3605"\w* \w whole|strong="H3605"\w* \w kingdom|strong="H4438"\w*.
